But further, so lateas the reign of James 1, Cambridge, its fields and its green commons can upon occasion be treated as an agrarian whole. In 1624 the vice-chancellor of the University and tbe Mayor of the Borough issued an ordinance touching the commons of the town. Every occupier of an ancient tenement having of old time broad gates may turn out two head of cattle. Every occupier of other tenements and cottages may turn out one. Every person having six score acres of land in Cambridge held may tum out six, and so in proportion for any greater or less quantity of land¹.
